body_text.text:
COVID-19 is rapidly spreading worldwide, and the number of cases in Europe is rising with increasing pace in several affected regions.1 While there is an urgent need to contain the pandemic to protect the elderly and vulnerable population, there are several obstacles to control the spread of new infections. The vast majority of SARS-CoV-2–infected individuals appear to have only mild to moderate symptoms similar to the flu or other flu-like infections,2, 3, 4, 5, 6 lacking defining symptoms. Thus, while we start losing the ability to trace all SARS-CoV-2–infected contacts, identification of potentially infected individuals becomes increasingly hard (Table 1
, Fig. 1
).
